article.description: Kelly Mazzante closed in on the Big Ten career scoring record, getting 19 points to help Penn State to a 68-56 victory Thursday night over Michigan.
article.headline: Mazzante needs 9 points for Big Ten record
article.linkText: Mazzante scores 19 in No. 8 Penn State win
article.story:
ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Penn State's Kelly Mazzante is closing
in on the all-time Big Ten women's scoring record, but all that
matters to her is that the Lady Lions keep winning.

Mazzante scored 19 points Thursday night to help lead No. 8 Penn
State to a 68-56 win against Michigan.

She now needs nine points to pass Ohio State's Katie Smith as
the Big Ten's all-time leading scorer, and she can get it Sunday,
when the Lady Lions (12-3, 5-0) host Illinois. Smith had 2,578
points in her career. Mazzante now has 2,570 career points.

"The record really is in the back of my mind," Mazzante said.
"My main focus is for us to win and let everything else take care
of itself."

Penn State coach Rene Portland said the record means a great
deal to her program, but respects Mazzante for keeping it in
perspective.

"I don't think she feels any pressure about it, not when she's
rewritten the whole record book," Portland said. "We're all
excited that she will have a chance to break the record at home."

The Lady Lions also got 16 points from Tanisha Wright and 11
from Amanda Brown.

Jennifer Smith led Michigan with 21 points. The Wolverines (9-8,
2-2) also got 19 points from Tabitha Pool and 14 from Stephanie
Gandy.

"We tried to battle them, but Penn State got a big score every
time they needed it," Michigan coach Cheryl Burnett said. "We
want to build a program like theirs. They pass well. They see the
floor well. That's where a lot of it starts."

The Lady Lions took control of the game during the final 12
minutes of the first half, when they overcame an 11-8 Michigan lead
with a 25-9 run to take a 33-20 lead at the break.

The Wolverines got as close as eight points with 10 minutes
remaining in the second half, but the Lady Lions responded that
charge with an 11-2 run.
